	<h2>Types of Automatic Gates</h2>

	<h3>Swing Gates</h3>
	<p>Swing gates operate like traditional doors, pivoting on hinges to open inward or outward. They're the most common residential choice.</p>

	<p><strong>Single Swing:</strong> One large panel swings open—ideal for narrower driveways up to 12 feet.</p>
	<p><strong>Double Swing:</strong> Two panels meet in the center and swing apart—suitable for driveways 12-20+ feet wide.</p>

	<p><strong>Advantages:</strong></p>
	<ul>
		<li>Classic, elegant appearance</li>
		<li>Generally less expensive than sliding gates</li>
		<li>Simpler mechanism with fewer moving parts</li>
		<li>Works well on flat or gently sloping driveways</li>
	</ul>

	<p><strong>Disadvantages:</strong></p>
	<ul>
		<li>Requires clearance space for swing arc</li>
		<li>Not ideal for sloped driveways</li>
		<li>Wind can affect operation</li>
		<li>May require longer driveway approach</li>
	</ul>

	<h3>Sliding Gates</h3>
	<p>Sliding gates move horizontally along a track, parallel to the fence line. They're popular for commercial properties and homes with space constraints.</p>

	<p><strong>V-Track Sliding:</strong> Gate rolls on wheels in a V-shaped ground track—most common type.</p>
	<p><strong>Cantilever Sliding:</strong> Gate hangs from an overhead track with no ground contact—ideal for uneven terrain or areas with debris.</p>

	<p><strong>Advantages:</strong></p>
	<ul>
		<li>No swing clearance required</li>
		<li>Works on sloped driveways</li>
		<li>Better wind resistance than swing gates</li>
		<li>Can span very wide openings</li>
	</ul>

	<p><strong>Disadvantages:</strong></p>
	<ul>
		<li>Requires lateral space equal to gate width</li>
		<li>Track requires maintenance (V-track style)</li>
		<li>More complex mechanism</li>
		<li>Generally higher cost</li>
	</ul>

